        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We aim to reach a flux limit of 50 microJy in band 7, which is best suited for our purpose with respect to sensitivity and wavelength range.

The requested sensitivity limit can be justified based on what is  known so far  about the spectral energy distribution (SED) of actively star-forming galaxies that hosted long GRBs. Several studies of members of our team have shown that these galaxies can have flux densities in the mm-band which are a factor of 100 to 1000 higher than in the uv/optical regime. So, even if these galaxies are  not seen down to, e.g., the 25th magnitude in R (0.3 microJy), they could still show up in ALMA's band 7. 

We ask for the best angular resolution in band 7 (maximum baseline) in order to obtain the best possible  astrometric accuracy for detected sources. 

We want to observe in the continuum since our main aim is to detect the sources. We do not know the redshifts of the first two targets, so we cannot optimize the position of the 4 subbands here with respect to the atmospheric transmission. To achive 50 microJy for a  point source in band 7 in dual polarization mode, ALMA's exposure time calculator predicts for this source in subband 1 at 336.5 GHz 15.98 min on target and 54.86 min in total, assuming standard weather conditions and 0.125 arcsec resolution (the minimum value that is accepted). No ACA time is requested. 

Adding together all our three targets, in total we request 169.72 min = 2.83 hrs telescope time.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
