    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Gamma-Ray Bursts (GRBs) are devided into long and short with the borderline at 2 seconds. Long GRBs are due to the collapse of massive stars while short GRBs are due to merging compact objects. This picture is supported by the fact that several short GRBs were found to be situated in elliptical galaxies, indicating that their progenitors belonged to an old population. On the other hand, about 50 percent of all short GRBs are hosted in star-forming galaxies. This rises the question about the age of this progenitor population. Models suggests a broad range, reaching from billions down to millions of years, with the latter naturally favoring star-forming galaxies. Here we propose to tackle this prediction by searching for the host galaxies of two short GRBs with so far no known optically identified host. We consider this as a pilot project, since a detection of these hosts would support the idea that a notable fraction of short-GRB progenitors belongs to a young stellar population, and would trigger more such studies. A positive result would also have implications for Gravitational Wave Observatories since it might increase the expected merger event rate in the local universe.</prp:abstract>
